The problem is that each time a test is run, a new instance of the test class is created, and new instances of the classes under test are created for its fields, which means the class variables for the IDs keep counting up. You can reset them to zero at the end of the test with an `@After` `tearDown` method, but you will need to access the private class variable via reflection.

    @After
    public void tearDown() throws Exception {
        Field classIdA = A.class.getDeclaredField(&quot;classId&quot;);
        classIdA.setAccessible(true);
        classIdA.setInt(null, 0);
        
        Field classIdB = B.class.getDeclaredField(&quot;classId&quot;);
        classIdB.setAccessible(true);
        classIdB.setInt(null, 0);
    }

This way, once each unit test finishes running, it will reset the state of each subclass to the status quo ante.

